<DocsLayout title="Conceptual Integrity" section="Concepts"><Hero eyebrow="Concept 01" title="Conceptual Integrity" lede="Complexity grows when responsibilities cross boundaries—not when the system has multiple components." reading="8 min" difficulty="Foundational" />
<Question>Can every team describe the system with the same simple sentence?</Question>
<Diagram title="One idea, clear boundaries" chart={chart} />
<Principle title="Keep the business deterministic. Keep intelligence bounded."><p>Workflow owns process. Business services own transactions. Agent owns uncertain decisions. Human owns irreversible approval.</p></Principle>
<CaseBlock title="The bid agent does not collect, save, approve, and push by itself."><p>Collection, normalization, deduplication, persistence, approval, and delivery remain deterministic. The agent performs one narrow decision: whether a notice deserves sales attention.</p></CaseBlock>
<Decision question="Why not build one autonomous agent?" answer="Because one agent would mix reasoning, permissions, transactions, and delivery. That makes failures hard to isolate and impossible to explain." alternative="No planner swarm. No universal memory layer. No second orchestration framework." />
<Takeaway>Do not add intelligence by breaking the system’s existing boundaries.</Takeaway></DocsLayout>
